<br>
Its true that there are other things that a warrior does, other than mashing the taunt button, but the sad thing that <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>I</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> found when playing a warrior was this: when the crap hit the fan I was relying on all of the <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>other</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> people on the group to use <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>their</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> class abilities and player skills to save the group.<br>
<br>
I, personally, found that playing a warrior didn't give me the class abilities to allow me to <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>use</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> the <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>player skills</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> that I have developed.  That was a very hard thing to admit, after having played a warrior for several years and many, many days /played: I liked playing my warrior, but I felt like I was playing with one hand tied behind my back.<br>
<br>
I mean no disrespect to any of you who find satisfaction playing your warrior! I, personally, just found that the warrior wasn't a versatile enough class for me to leverage the player skills that I have developed over three and a half years of playing this game.<br>
